Otherwise fantastic course and learnt a lot :)

Overall, excellent intro to matlab. Feeling much better about it!

column3: Programming and data analysis using Matlab
column5:
- A schedule of the two days so we could coordinate meetings/phone calls if we still needed to work, in our breaks.

- A little more clarity around some content (esp loops and conditionals). 

- A bit more clarity about the input required for scalar vs vector syntax for different functions/scripts. ie a 'cheat sheet' guide for "This is how you enter things for vectors", "This is how you enter things for scalars" to make the programming a little easter, so you don't get stuck on something that simple and waste time rifling for the answer.

column3: Programming and data analysis using Matlab
column5:
Very good workshop for people with no experience with MATLAB at all. Would surely recommend it to anyone trying to start using MATLAB. I would try to adjust the pace in the more difficult sections ('especially the 'for loops' section).
Also I would go through the answers of all the challenges after finishing them, just to be sure we are thinking the right (and the most simple) way. Sometimes I feel there is a much better option to solve things in MATLAB than what I initially think. I would emphasize that.

Again. thank you very much!

column5:
As an introduction course I felt it somewhat missed the mark. It was both too techncal for the beginner and not enough information for the more intermediate user. It was a nice intro to some basics of NeCTAR as well as gave some key insights into Spartan. I would have liked to hear more about migrating our existing Edward workflows to Spartan and gaining some insights into best practices on this new chimera platform.  I also would have preferred to hear more insights on why I would want to use NeCTAR (what computational problems would it help me solve), what resources are available for how long (and how much) beyond the training profile, and what 'typical' users are using it for.

Across the board, the how-to guides and on-line resources were great.

column3: Introduction to UniMelb HPC and Introduction to the NeCTAR Cloud
column5:
I'm sure this sort of class is very tricky because the participants will have such widely varying experience and computing requirements. What would have helped me personally (rusty but comfortable with the idea of command line interface, newcomer to both Melbourne Uni and HPC and cloud computing) was a short orientation, with brief examples, of what situations would suit Spartan vs a Nectar cloud instance, what the differences/similarities are, etc. I have specific interests in the facilities for Monte Carlo simulations in statistics (HPC I assume) but also always interested in knowing what else is available that can be put to unanticipated good use.
I acknowledge this might have been boring for those well used to the unimelb system though. 

I may have missed the interconnections between the alternating Nectar and HPC sessions. Setting up the demo Nectar instance was good practical stuff. I wasn't sure why that was separated by the HPC segments. 
I don't know exactly what, but something similarly hands-on for setting up a simple HPC job might have been good? In two separate halves?
(Again acknowledging the Edward veterans might have been bored...)

Overall a beneficial course though, nicely taught. It's great to know you guys are there for this.

It's probably really hard for you guys to know exactly where to pitch at, with the various levels of technical expertise in your audience. And I think it was good you guys adapted to the skills of your audience as the lesson went on. I totally got this and I think you guys handled a difficult problem well, but I was still left wishing we could have gone a little deeper.

So here are a couple things I think would have been or could be cool:

- Direction to some "further reading," or something: We covered some of the basic data analysis and wrangling techniques, which is obviously where to start and there's only so much time, and so on. Still, it kind of left me with the question, "What next?" What are some cool ways of analysing text data? I know PDFs are a pain - how should I deal with them? This kind of stuff is beyond the scope of a one-day course and, well, there's the internet, but God, there's so much of the internet - it can really help having someone direct you to three or four links that can help you take the next step.

- "Advanced NLTK" or "NLTK for programmers": I know demand would be limited, but as more people take to NLTK? I don't know. A more advanced session would be neat, if you guys can muster the people together.

Have some cheat sheets to take home at the end, as a handy reference guide (ideally soft copy so we can ctrl f). Make it not so late in the semester, omg, so many things!! But aside from that it was great and the trainers were fab.

I would change the whole set up to presenting a research question and how to use R to answer the research question just like in the real world. 

Research Question: What were the characteristics of the people who were more likely to die on the titanic? (or something similar)

Using R to answer the above question
- tour of the R page
- flow of cohersion
- importing data - the titanic file
- saving files
- cleaning data- how to look at the outliers in the dataset
- looking at central tendency - of the variables to answer the question
- creating graphs - to help answer the quesiton
- creating tables to answer the question
- how to create variables to answer the question
- and then the more interesting aspects of R - eg. piping to answer the above question

 I feel as R was so foreign to what I have done before, I feel that I could understand it better if I could attach what you were doing to something that I was familiar with. At the moment, I felt that R was taught in pieces and a bit abstract.  There were some examples with the titanic but no real overarching research question, some examples with cats, some examples with lucky numbers, some examples with temperature - it jumped all over the place and made it harder to follow for a beginner - cognitive overload :)

However, I think the whole concept of ResBaz is fantastic and that it's great that you are asking for feedback. Keep up the good work!

column5: The presenters really need to learn some proper education skills. They are very passionate and knowledgeable, but they clearly don't know how to teach beginners. Many of the students were totally left behind. Simple educational techniques would have helped here, e.g. use the whiteboard to list each LINUX command as it's introduced. Many times the presenters slipped into jargon, which wasn't  explained properly. A lot of the extraneous history could have been left out. The handout was very useful.. perhaps considering building on this. For example, you could set up some basic exercises that a beginner could follow which would explore the fundamental concepts behind LINUX and HPC systems - navigating directory trees, looking at text files, shell scripts, batch submission, etc. Explanations of the HPC concept were generally very good - the analogy of "one powerful horse" vs "many horses" was well presented.

column162:
Overall I would not change much. However, an additional nice touch may be : everyone gets given data of something, maybe everyone gets emailed a small video file. Then they have to download a premade analysis script. The teacher could then run through how to use premade scripts to go through more complex data types. Maybe break down the script and teach how to analyse the codes sections and to learn what each part does. so you can modify it to fit the demands of your research analysis. 

I just think it would be a nice touch because a lot of beginners won't actually have to write much scripts, they will just be downloading premade ones for pipeline analysis of big data sets. So I think thier application and modification would be a nice additional aspect for the course. Maybe in for a part 3 workshop? 
It is just a thought though.

column30:
1. Pre reading was very useful.
2. The trainer Pablo was very clear and engaging.
3. Course material taught in the class was at a suitable beginner level, and very relevant to my work.
4. Volunteers were amazing! Very helpful to have them in the room. Without them, I would have completely fallen behind about three times. Thanks to them, I was able to keep up with the class.
Thank you. Fantastic to have this course on offer, and amazing it is free!
column31:
1. Allow us into the room at least 20 minutes before. We only had about two minutes to set up before Pablo started talking. Luckily I had set everything up on my laptop the night before (launched R Studio, opened the recommended R cheat sheets, a file for taking notes, and ensured my computer would have internet), but if I hadn't had done this, I would have been behind from the beginning.
2. Pablo types very fast. Slow it down just a little bit, or breath :-), to allow us mere mortal typers to catch up. The three times when I fell behind, it was because of a typo in my code or a forgotten comma, due to rushing. We finished 15 minutes early for lunch and 20 minutes early at end of day, so there was time for a small reduction in speed.
